Adapter design — three adapters under one toolkit:
  Rather than threading a slug discriminator through one giant
  poll() function, the file exports three separate PollAdapter
  objects, each registered under one event slug. The framework's
  (toolkit, event)→adapter Map keeps them straight; the registry's
  duplicate-event guard fires per event slug so three non-
  overlapping events register cleanly.

Adapter 1 — NOTION_PAGE_ADDED_TRIGGER:
  ✓ initialState: anchors last_seen_edited at now() + empty
    last_seen_page_ids. No config required (workspace-wide search).
  ✓ poll: NOTION_SEARCH with filter={property:'object',value:'page'},
    sort={direction:'descending',timestamp:'last_edited_time'},
    page_size:50. Paginates via start_cursor + has_more.
  ✓ Emits one event per page whose last_edited_time >= lastSeen
    (skipping the boundary-id dedupe set). Payload
    { page, page_id, last_edited_time }.
  ✓ State + boundary-id pattern matches F.5/F.6 (id-aware drop on
    boundary ms equality + merge-old-with-new when high-water
    doesn't advance).

Adapter 2 — NOTION_PAGE_ADDED_TO_DATABASE:
  ✓ initialState: anchors last_seen_created at now().
  ✓ poll: requires config.database_id (throws cleanly when missing —
    test asserts). Calls NOTION_QUERY_DATABASE with sorts=
    [{timestamp:'created_time',direction:'descending'}], page_size:100.
    Paginates via start_cursor.
  ✓ Uses created_time (correctly distinguishes new-page from edit-
    to-existing-page; spec literal mandates this).
  ✓ Payload { page, page_id, database_id, created_time }.

Adapter 3 — NOTION_COMMENTS_ADDED_TRIGGER:
  ✓ initialState: anchors last_seen_created at now() + empty
    last_seen_comment_ids.
  ✓ poll: requires config.block_id (throws cleanly when missing —
    test asserts). Calls NOTION_LIST_COMMENTS with block_id +
    page_size:100 + start_cursor.
  ✓ Comment IDs are UUIDs (not ordered) — adapter uses created_time
    as high-water + boundary-id set for same-ms dedupe.
  ✓ Payload { comment, comment_id, page_id (=block_id),
    created_time }.

